JOHANNESBURG – Former Constitutional Court Justice Albie Sachs was one of the chief architects of South Africa’s Constitution. Sachs told eNCA the Constitution  was engineered to uphold our democratic institutions and protect the vulnerable from abuse. The retired Constitutional Court judge said he was proud of the way these inbuilt protective mechanisms have have stood firm this year, despite being severely tested. Sachs went into exile, where he lost his arm and sight in one eye when apartheid agents in Maputo planted a bomb in his car in 1988. He returned to South Africa 24 years later to serve on the ANC’s National Executive Committee, where he was tasked with his most important - helping to draft the Constitution at the Convention for a Democratic South Africa – Codesa. WATCH: Exclusive interview with Albie Sachs * Watch the interview by Annika Larsen in the video gallery above eNCA